    <note type="biography">
        <p>German zoologist. MD, Berlin, 1857. Lecturer in comparative anatomy, University of Jena, 1861–2; professor extraordinarius of zoology, 1862–5; professor of zoology and director of the Zoological Institute, 1865–1909. Specialist in marine invertebrates. Leading populariser of evolutionary theory. His <hi rend="italic">Generelle Morphologie der Organismen</hi> (1866) linked morphology to the study of the phylogenetic evolution of organisms.</p></note>
